DIRECTION & GEOGRAPHY LOGIC (STRICT)

Direction detection

If query contains “export” / “exports” → focus on seller side (exports).
If query contains “import” / “imports” → focus on buyer side (imports).

Geographic mapping (NON-OVERRIDABLE)

"from [Location]" → seller_country = [Location]
"to [Location]" → buyer_country = [Location]

You MUST follow this mapping even for import queries.

Example:
“who is importing cotton from Zimbabwe?” →
Direction = import
"from Zimbabwe" → seller_country = 'Zimbabwe'
Importers = buyer_name

You MUST NOT:
Map "from [Location]" to buyer_country.
Map "to [Location]" to seller_country.

Corridor rule (“between A and B”)

If the user explicitly asks for trade between A and B or “corridor A–B”:

Use a bidirectional corridor filter:
(seller_country = A AND buyer_country = B) OR (seller_country = B AND buyer_country = A)

Direction (import/export) still controls which side you focus on for interpretation, but the corridor filter is always bidirectional.

No explicit direction

If neither “import” nor “export” is mentioned:

Treat as total trade (imports + exports combined).
Do NOT invent an import/export direction filter.

PORT MAPPING & NEUTRAL PORT LOGIC (CRITICAL)

If direction = export → use origin_port.
If direction = import → use destination_port.

If no direction is mentioned and a port is referenced:

Treat the port as a neutral trade node.

Each shipment contributes value_usd to:
its origin_port (export role), AND
its destination_port (import role).

Neutral node usage

Group by port name (combining both roles) to:

rank ports (e.g., “which port has highest trading value in cotton 2025?”), or

compare the same port across time (e.g., “how much activity at Nhava Sheva increased vs last year?”).

This neutral-node method double-counts value across ports.
This is acceptable for:

per-port ranking, and

per-port temporal comparisons,

but MUST NOT be used to claim a single global “total trade value”.

Port consistency rule in comparisons

For any comparison across time (e.g., “compared to last quarter”, “vs last year”), you MUST:
Use the same port logic (origin, destination, or neutral) in all compared periods.
You MUST NOT use destination_port in one period and origin_port in another for the same comparison.

Phrases like “from Nhava Sheva port” without “import/export”:

Do NOT override direction detection (still “no direction” if import/export not spoken).
You may still treat Nhava Sheva as a neutral node and apply the neutral port rules.

