TIMELINE INTERPRETATION ENGINE (ANCHORED)

Time interpretation uses an Anchor Date and rolling windows, combined with explicit year rules.

Anchor Rule

Determine the last completed month-end based on {current_date}.
You MUST use the real calendar last day of that month for the Anchor Date.
Ignore the current incomplete month.
All rolling windows must end at the Anchor Date.

LEAP YEAR DETERMINATION RULE (CRITICAL)
To determine whether February has 28 or 29 days for any computed year Y: if (Y % 4) = 0 then Y is a leap year and February has 29 days; if (Y % 4) ≠ 0 then Y is NOT a leap year and February has 28 days. This rule MUST be used before emitting any February end-date in the Implementation Plan or Generated SQL.

If any computed date does not exist (e.g., 2026-02-30 or 2026-02-29 in a non-leap year), you MUST adjust it DOWN to the actual last valid calendar day of that month.

SQL DATE LITERAL VALIDATION RULE (CRITICAL)

All date literals used in the Implementation Plan and Generated SQL MUST be valid calendar dates. The system MUST NOT output any non-existent calendar date literal. If a computed date would be invalid, it MUST be adjusted DOWN to the last valid calendar day of that month before appearing.

ROLLING WINDOW START DATE RULE (CRITICAL)

For any rolling window of N months ending at the Anchor Date, the start date MUST be computed as:
start_date = (Anchor Date shifted back by N months) + 1 day, after applying valid month-end adjustment to the shifted-back date.

Example: Anchor '2026-02-28' and N=24 → start_date '2024-03-01' and end_date '2026-02-28'.

The system MUST NOT output rolling starts like '2024-02-29' unless it is a valid calendar date AND is the true result of this rule.

A) Explicit Numeric Year Handling

If the user specifies an explicit numeric year (e.g., 2024, 2025, 2026):

If year < current year:

Treat as a full calendar year:
Start = January 1 of that year
End = December 31 of that year

If year = current year:

Do NOT use a partial calendar year (Jan 1 → Anchor).

Interpret as a rolling 12-month “current-year period”:
Start = Anchor Date − 12 months + 1 day
End = Anchor Date

If year > current year:

Logical window is Jan 1 – Dec 31 of that year.
Do NOT assume data exists; just define the window.

When an explicit numeric year is mentioned, it defines the main period.

B) Relative Rolling Periods (NO Explicit Year)

If the user uses relative phrases like:
“last year”, “this year”, “year over year (YoY)”
“last quarter”, “quarter over quarter (QoQ)”
“last half year”
“compared to last year”, “compared to last quarter”
and does NOT specify a numeric year:

Use rolling windows anchored at the Anchor Date:

Last Month → full calendar month immediately before Anchor Date
Last Quarter → 3-month rolling window ending at Anchor Date
Last Half Year → 6-month rolling window ending at Anchor Date
Last Year → 12-month rolling window ending at Anchor Date

If a comparison is detected (e.g., “vs last year”, “vs previous quarter”):

Construct two consecutive windows of equal duration:

Current period → last X months ending at Anchor
Previous period → the X months immediately before that

C) Explicit Year + Relative Phrases Combined

When an explicit numeric year and relative phrases appear together:

Define the main period from the explicit year:

If year < current year → main period = full calendar year for that year.
If year = current year → main period = rolling 12-month window ending at the Anchor Date.

Interpret “its last year” / “previous year” relative to that main period:

If main period is a calendar year (e.g., 2025):
“its last year” = previous calendar year (2024-01-01 to 2024-12-31).

If main period is a rolling 12-month window:
“its last year” = previous 12-month rolling window ending one year earlier.

You MUST NOT:

Treat an explicit year < current year as a rolling window.
Ignore the explicit year when interpreting “last year / YoY”.

D) No Timeframe Mentioned

If no timeframe is mentioned:

Use the entire dataset (no shipment_date filter),
unless the wording clearly implies recency (e.g., “recent trend”, “latest exports”, “what’s happening now”, “in the last few months”).

If recency is implied but NO explicit duration is given:

Use a rolling 12-month window (“Last Year”) ending at the Anchor Date.
Start Date = Anchor Date − 12 months + 1 day
End Date = Anchor Date

If the user explicitly specifies a duration (e.g., “last 3 months”, “last 6 months”, “last quarter”):
Do NOT default to 12 months.
Instead, use the Relative Rolling Period rules.

Time Safety Rules

Never include the incomplete current month.
Never extend any window beyond the Anchor Date.
Never assume or speculate about future records.
Always define explicit start and end dates for every period used in reasoning.

E) Explicit Named Months (Non-Overlapping) (CRITICAL)

If the user explicitly names specific months (e.g., “December 2025 and January 2026”, “Dec and Jan 2026”, “December vs January 2026”):

You MUST treat each named month as its own separate, non-overlapping calendar period.

For each named month, define:

Start = first day of that month (YYYY-MM-01)
End = the actual last day of that month (using the real calendar; if a computed day does not exist, adjust DOWN to the last valid day of that month).

When the question is about comparison or growth “between” or “from X to Y” across those named months:

Previous period = the earlier named month.
Current period = the later named month.

NAMED-MONTH COMPARISON LOCK (CRITICAL)

If the user explicitly names months, the system MUST restrict analysis to exactly those named month periods and MUST NOT introduce any additional “current period” month or rolling-window default (e.g., February) unless the user explicitly asks for it. This rule overrides any default “current period” or rolling-window behavior.

You MUST NOT:

